  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Introduction to Daf 114 and Shechutei Chutz with Special Cases",
      "display_title": "Shechutei Chutz Overview",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening remarks on Daf 114 and the perek on Shechutei Chutz",
          "display_title": "Opening & Context",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Discussion of Parah Adumah and Seir Hamishtaleach as exceptions to Shechutei Chutz",
          "display_title": "Parah & Seir Exceptions",
          "timestamp": "00:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "Mishna's examples of invalidities: blemished animals, idolatry, bestiality; Rabbi Shimon's position on future fitness",
          "display_title": "Mishna Invalidities",
          "timestamp": "01:18"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Shimon's Principle: Mechusar Zman and the Middle Ground Between Karet and No Violation",
      "display_title": "Rabbi Shimon & Mechusar…",
      "timestamp": "02:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Shimon's principle that things unfit now but fit later incur lav without karet",
          "display_title": "Shimon's Principle",
          "timestamp": "02:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Examples of mechusar zman: passing blemish, oto v'et bno, birds too young, time not yet ripe",
          "display_title": "Mechusar Zman Examples",
          "timestamp": "02:03"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's analysis: why must the debate be specified in all three cases of blemishes, oto v'et bno, and birds",
          "display_title": "Three Cases Analysis",
          "timestamp": "03:11"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Source for Rabbi Shimon: The Devarim Verse on Centralized Offerings and Bamot",
      "display_title": "Lo Ta'asun Verse Source",
      "timestamp": "06:58",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Ilai and Reish Lakish cite Deuteronomy 12:8 as source for Rabbi Shimon's reasoning",
          "display_title": "Devarim 12:8 Citation",
          "timestamp": "06:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Explanation of lo ta'asun ke-chol asher anachnu osim: prohibiting private bamot in the wilderness versus centralized place",
          "display_title": "Lo Ta'asun Reading",
          "timestamp": "07:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "How the verse mandates only voluntary offerings (nedavot) on bamot, not obligatory ones (chovot)",
          "display_title": "Nedavot vs Chovot",
          "timestamp": "09:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gilgal as mechusar zman with respect to Shilo: obligatory sacrifices forbidden during heter bamot at Gilgal",
          "display_title": "Gilgal & Shilo Analysis",
          "timestamp": "10:20"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Addressing the Contradiction: Mechusar Zman as Only an Aseh, Not a Lo Ta'aseh",
      "display_title": "Aseh vs Lo Ta'aseh Debate",
      "timestamp": "14:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yirmya objects: if lo ta'asun creates a prohibition, one should receive lashes (malku)",
          "display_title": "Yirmya's Objection",
          "timestamp": "14:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Zeira's answer: the verse transforms it into an aseh only, not a lo ta'aseh",
          "display_title": "Zeira's Resolution",
          "timestamp": "14:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Principle from Chullin: slaughtering mechusar zman in the mikdash is only an aseh, not subject to lashes",
          "display_title": "Chullin Parallel",
          "timestamp": "14:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "For Rabbi Shimon: lo ta'asun remains a lo ta'aseh, subject to malku even at Gilgal",
          "display_title": "Shimon's Lashes",
          "timestamp": "17:54"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Nachman bar Yitzchak: panim of Gilgal compared to Shilo is considered chutz (outside), explaining aseh status only inside the Mikdash",
          "display_title": "Gilgal as Outside",
          "timestamp": "18:32"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rava's Source for Rabbi Shimon: Pesach Sacrifice Before its Time",
      "display_title": "Pesach Before Time Source",
      "timestamp": "23:01",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Baraita: Rabbi Shimon proves from Pesach that mechusar zman during issur bamot creates a lav",
          "display_title": "Pesach Proof",
          "timestamp": "23:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Deuteronomy 16: lo tuchal lizboach et haPesach in any of your gates—centralization mandate",
          "display_title": "Lo Tuchal Pesach",
          "timestamp": "23:31"
        },
        {
          "title": "Question: why need special source if issur bamot already forbids? Discussion of before vs after chatzot",
          "display_title": "Pesach Timing Question",
          "timestamp": "24:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's alternative reading: after chatzot (after Pesach time), issur applies automatically; before chatzot shows mechusar zman prohibition",
          "display_title": "Before Chatzot Scenario",
          "timestamp": "25:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Issur bamah for Pesach vs heter bamah for other offerings: Pesach remains forbidden during heter bamot because it is chovah",
          "display_title": "Pesach Always Forbidden",
          "timestamp": "26:30"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Mishna's Discussion of Owners Not Yet Ready: Zav, Zavah, Yoledet",
      "display_title": "Mechusar Zman Be'Bealim",
      "timestamp": "34:12",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Examples of mechusar zman due to owner status: zav, zavah, yoledet not yet at their permitted time",
          "display_title": "Owner Status Examples",
          "timestamp": "34:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Principle: yoledet's chatas before her time not ra'uy lepesach ohel moed; olah is ra'uy because olot can be brought by others",
          "display_title": "Yoledet's Sacrifices",
          "timestamp": "34:18"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's addition: Metzora to list (via Zeiri) because Metzora brings asham; rejection of Nazir addition (not tamei like others)",
          "display_title": "Metzora Inclusion",
          "timestamp": "35:44"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Asham Shelo Lishmo: Can Redefining an Asham as an Olah Make a Mechusar Zman Sacrifice Valid?",
      "display_title": "Asham Shelo Lishmo",
      "timestamp": "37:20",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Chilkiya: asham brought outside is patur only if slaughtered lishmo; if shelo lishmo (as olah) then chayav",
          "display_title": "Chilkiya's Rule",
          "timestamp": "37:20"
        },
        {
          "title": "Reasoning: asham shelo lishmo inside mikdash would be kasher, so outside with different intent it becomes ra'uy lepesach ohel moed",
          "display_title": "Identity Change Logic",
          "timestamp": "37:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's objection: if lishmo outside is patur, shouldn't shelo lishmo outside also be patur since it could be kasher?",
          "display_title": "Initial Objection",
          "timestamp": "39:43"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara's answer: ba'i akira—identity doesn't change until actually slaughtered shelo lishmo; as asham it remains patur",
          "display_title": "Identity Not Changed",
          "timestamp": "40:27"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rav Huna's challenge: is there anything that is not kasher lishmo but kasher shelo lishmo? The difficulty with asham becoming kasher when called olah",
          "display_title": "Rav Huna's Challenge",
          "timestamp": "41:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "Pesach example: when brought outside Pesach season, it becomes shelamim and is kasher shelo lishmo",
          "display_title": "Pesach Analogy",
          "timestamp": "42:23"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
